            <h1 class="block1">Web Development Report</h1>
            <p class="inline1">In this report, we will explore various aspects of web development.</p>

            <h2 class="block2">Opening Developer's Console</h2>
            <p class="inline2">To open the developer's console in Mozilla Firefox, you can press <strong>F12</strong> or right-click on the webpage and select "Inspect". In Safari, you can access the developer tools by going to <strong>Develop > Show Web Inspector</strong>.</p>

            <h2 class="block2">Internal Links in HTML</h2>
            <p class="inline2">Generally, using relative links for internal linking is preferable as it makes the website more portable and easier to maintain. Absolute links are useful when linking to resources on external websites. Use cases for choosing absolute links include linking to specific external resources that may change their URL frequently. Relative links are beneficial for linking within the same website structure, ensuring that the links remain valid even if the site structure changes.</p>

            <h2 class="block2">Image Formats in Web Development</h2>
            <p class="inline1">There are several image formats commonly used in web development:</p>
			<ul>
                <li class="bg-hex"><strong>JPG (or JPEG):</strong> Suitable for photographs or images with many colors. It uses lossy compression, making file sizes smaller but with some loss of quality.</li>
                <li class="bg-hex"><strong>GIF:</strong> Ideal for simple graphics with few colors or animations. It supports transparency and animation but has a limited color palette.</li>
                <li class="bg-gradient"><strong>PNG:</strong> Best for images with sharp edges, text, or transparency. It uses lossless compression, maintaining high quality but resulting in larger file sizes compared to JPG.</li>
                <li class="bg-gradient"><strong>WEBP:</strong> An image format developed by Google that offers both lossy and lossless compression. It provides smaller file sizes with high quality and supports animation and transparency.</li>
                <li class="bg-image"><strong>SVG:</strong> Scalable Vector Graphics format that uses XML-based vector images. SVG images are resolution-independent and can be scaled without losing quality. They are suitable for logos, icons, and graphics that need to be displayed at different sizes.</li>
                <li><img src="fortask.png" alt="none.png" width="1700" height="600"></li>
		    </ul>
